title: Commission Regulation (EEC) No 1533/92 of 12 June 1992 concerning the classification of certain goods in the Combined Nomenclature
header:
16.6.1992 EN Official Journal of the European Communities L 162/5
COMMISSION REGULATION (EEC) No 1533/92
of 12 June 1992
concerning the classification of certain goods in the combined nomenclature
THE COMMISSION OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES
main_body: The goods described in column 1 of the annexed table are now classified within the combined nomenclature under the appropriate CN codes indicated in column 2 of the said table.

Binding tariff information issued by the customs authorities of Member States which do not conform to the rights established by this Regulation can continue to be invoked under the provisions of Article 6 of Regulation (EEC) No 3796/90 for a period of three months by the holder if a binding contract has been concluded as envisaged in Article 14 (3) (a) or (b) of Regulation (EEC) No 1715/90.

This Regulation shall enter into force on the 21st day following its publication in the Official Journal of the European Communities.
This Regulation shall be binding in its entirety and directly applicable in all Member States.
attachments:
Done at Brussels, 12 June 1992.
For the Commission
Christiane SCRIVENER

ANNEX
Description of goods Classification CN code Reasons
1. Pale yellow powder, with the taste of dried milk, having the following analytical characteristics (percentage by weight):
Milkfat 11,4
Lowfat milk solids 85,9
Water 2,7
Proteins (N x 6,38) 30,6
Lactose 42,9
Phosphorlipides (P x 26) 17
2. Cooked preparation of pig meat consisting of a pinkish/brown meat mass containing pieces of meat up to 6 cm in size, pieces of fat and gelatine.
3. Food preparation in the form of a water in milk fat emulsion consisting of:
— milk fats
— water
— sodium caseinate
— gelatine
— salt
— emulsifiers
4. Preparation consisting mainly of a mixture of approximately 60 % hexacalcium trisodium pentakis (ortho-phosphate), by weight, and approximately 40 % tricalcium bis (orthophospate), by weight, used in animal feed
5. Primidon (INN)
6. Solid extract of the residual material insoluble in aliphatic solvents obtained during the extraction of rosin from wood, having the following characteristics:
— a resin acid content by weight not exceeding 30 %,
— an acid number not exceeding 110, and
— a melting point of not less than 100 o C.
